label: Marriages - 1632-1720
description: Box 4 - Marriages contains records created in Florida during the seventeenth and early-eighteenth centuries.  All records in Box 4 contain information on Indians, Blacks, Spaniards, and Creoles. These marriage records range from 18 January 1632 to 23 May 1720 and have several sets of pagination. At a minimum, each entry records the names of the bride and groom; the date of the marriage; the name and title of the priest; and if the bride and/or groom is not white, then his and/or her skin color or racial designation (negro/a, moreno/a, pardo/a, indio/a [sometimes only referred to as a natural], chino/a [meaning mestizo/a]); if an individual is a slave. Additional information includes, but is not limited to, the following: parents' names, nationalities, places of previous residence, and/or current residence; time of day the marriage was performed; military rank and/or administrative title of any male named in the entry; name and title of priest who performed the diligencias (marriage investigations), read the tres amonestaciones (banns of marriage), and performed the wedding; names of padrinos/testigos (witnesses); the calendar days on which the tres amonestacioneswere read; if an Indian, then from which province or chiefdom (e.g., Guale); whether there were impediments to the marriage; legitimacy of individual's birth; if parents are deceased; if slave, owner's name; and where the ceremony was performed.
